1
00:00:04,620 --> 00:00:08,460
The visualizations you create will give you insights into

2
00:00:08,460 --> 00:00:11,914
the data that you can't get from descriptive statistics.

3
00:00:11,914 --> 00:00:15,940
A plot can immediately tell you if your data is symmetric or skewed,

4
00:00:15,940 --> 00:00:18,459
if it is unimodal or multimodal.

5
00:00:18,459 --> 00:00:24,125
Plots can also indicate interesting areas for further investigation and clarification.

6
00:00:24,125 --> 00:00:28,110
Categories in a bar chart with low counts might point to errors in

7
00:00:28,110 --> 00:00:32,605
the data or if you see that bars have values that counter your expectations,

8
00:00:32,605 --> 00:00:37,925
then that might point towards further research or a revisiting of data assumptions.

9
00:00:37,925 --> 00:00:43,205
For example, let's say you're looking at a distribution of user birth months.

10
00:00:43,205 --> 00:00:45,290
Seeing an unusually large number of

11
00:00:45,290 --> 00:00:49,770
January responses might suggest a deeper investigation such as whether

12
00:00:49,770 --> 00:00:51,810
there are a lot of users who are just submitting

13
00:00:51,810 --> 00:00:56,780
default information or if there's something wrong with how the data has been recorded.

14
00:00:56,780 --> 00:01:00,680
In a histogram, one of the most salient bits of information

15
00:01:00,680 --> 00:01:04,660
that you can observe is whether or not there are outliers in your data.

16
00:01:04,660 --> 00:01:07,520
If the plot covers an unexpected range,

17
00:01:07,520 --> 00:01:12,700
this can point to the presence of unusual points that are worth further investigation.

18
00:01:12,700 --> 00:01:16,145
In some cases, like if you have highly skewed data,

19
00:01:16,145 --> 00:01:18,790
you might want to change the range of the data plotted in

20
00:01:18,790 --> 00:01:21,920
order to zoom into parts that are more interesting.

21
00:01:21,920 --> 00:01:24,690
Rather than filtering on the original data,

22
00:01:24,690 --> 00:01:28,530
you can simply make changes to the axis limits to make your observations.

23
00:01:28,530 --> 00:01:33,275
Let's say that we make a plot of ride durations in minutes for a bike-sharing service,

24
00:01:33,275 --> 00:01:35,595
and obtain a plot as shown.

25
00:01:35,595 --> 00:01:39,415
There are a few outliers in the last bar from 1,400 to

26
00:01:39,415 --> 00:01:44,455
1,500 minutes that cause all of the other points to be fit into the first bar.

27
00:01:44,455 --> 00:01:47,805
While we might want to look at those outlier points later,

28
00:01:47,805 --> 00:01:50,140
we could first just change the axis limits

29
00:01:50,140 --> 00:01:53,170
to see the shape of where most of the data points lie.

30
00:01:53,170 --> 00:01:56,145
When we limit the access to 60 minutes,

31
00:01:56,145 --> 00:01:58,195
and use bins of five-minutes wide,

32
00:01:58,195 --> 00:01:59,900
we get a clear picture that

33
00:01:59,900 --> 00:02:04,790
the typical ride length lies between five and 15-minute range.

